Data Wrangling

You will need to download two datasets from https://github.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data. The individual and regional CHS datasets in 01_chs. The individual data includes personal and health characteristics of children in 12 communities across Southern California. The regional data include air quality measurements at the community level. Once downloaded, you can merge these datasets using the location variable. Once combined, you will need to do the following:

library(data.table)
indiv <- data.table::fread("/Users/vikaskunta/Downloads/chs_individual.csv")
region <- data.table::fread("/Users/vikaskunta/Downloads/chs_regional.csv")
merged <- merge(indiv, region, by="townname", all=FALSE)

    find_mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}
cat <- c("asthma", "father_asthma", "mother_asthma", "wheeze", "hayfever", "allergy", "educ_parent", "smoke", "gasstove")
contin <- c("agepft", "height", "weight", "bmi", "fev", "fvc", "mmef", "pm2_5_fr", "no_24hr")
imputemerge <- merged %>%
  group_by(male, hispanic) %>%
  mutate(across(all_of(cat), 
                ~ ifelse(is.na(.), as.character(find_mode(as.character(.))), .)),
         across(all_of(contin), 
                ~ ifelse(is.na(.), mean(., na.rm = TRUE), .))) %>%
ungroup()

  2. Create a new categorical variable named "obesity_level" using the BMI measurement (underweight BMI<14; normal BMI 14-22; overweight BMI 22-24; obese BMI>24). To make sure the variable is rightly coded, create a summary table that contains the minimum BMI, maximum BMI, and the total number of observations per category.

    obesity_level <- function(bmi) {
  ifelse(bmi < 14, "Underweight", ifelse(bmi >= 14 & bmi < 22, "Normal", ifelse(bmi >= 22 & bmi < 24, "Overweight", "Obese")))
}
imputemerge <- imputemerge %>%
  mutate(obesity_level = obesity_level(bmi))

BMIsummarytable <- imputemerge %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarize(
    minimumBMI = min(bmi, na.rm = TRUE),
    maximumBMI = max(bmi, na.rm = TRUE),
    nBMI = n()
  )

  3. Create another categorical variable named "smoke_gas_exposure" that summarizes "Second Hand Smoke" and "Gas Stove." The variable should have four categories in total.

    imputemerge <- imputemerge %>%
  mutate(smoke_gas_exposure = case_when(
    smoke == 0 & gasstove == 0 ~ "No Smoke Nor Gas Exposure",
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 0 ~ "Second-Hand Smoke Exposure",
    smoke == 0 & gasstove == 1 ~ "Gas Stove Exposure",
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 1 ~ "Both Second-Hand Smoke and Gas Stove Exposure"
  ))

It looks like it could be somewhat linear as BMI increases, FEV seems to as well but the potential outliers to the right of the graph may nullify that.

Visualization

Create the following figures and interpret them. Be sure to include easily understandable axes, titles, and legends.

  1. Facet plot showing scatterplots with regression lines of BMI vs FEV by "townname".

    library(ggplot2)
ggplot(imputemerge, aes(x = bmi, y = fev)) +
  geom_point() +

    Each town has a positive regression trend in similar direction and shapes but some towns such as Mira Loma and Lake Gregory and Atascadero are a lot more scattered than the others while a town like Riverside a vast majority of results are in the lower BMI portion of the x asis. There seems to be a couple of extreme BMI values in each one but almost all the graphs show a over 90% of subjects below the 25 BMI mark.

  2. Stacked histograms of FEV by BMI category and FEV by smoke/gas exposure. Use different color schemes than the ggplot default.

    color_bmi <- c("lightgreen", "red", "purple", "darkblue")
color_smokegas <- c("maroon", "skyblue", "orange", "darkgreen")

ggplot(imputemerge, aes(x = fev, fill = factor(obesity_level))) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "stack", alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = color_bmi) +
  labs(x = "FEV", y = "Count", fill = "BMI Category") +
  ggtitle("Stacked Histogram of FEV by BMI Category")

    ggplot(imputemerge, aes(x = fev, fill = factor(smoke_gas_exposure))) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "stack", alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = color_smokegas) +
  labs(x = "FEV", y = "Count", fill = "Smoke/Gas Exposure") +
  ggtitle("Stacked Histogram of FEV by Smoke/Gas Exposure")

    The BMI stacked histogram is showing a majority of the results in the normal category of BMI showing the highest frequencies. The smoke/gas exposure stacked histogram is showing a majority of the results in the gas stove exposure and both second hand smoke and gas stove exposure categories are showing the highest frequencies.

  3. Barchart of BMI by smoke/gas exposure.

    ggplot(imputemerge, aes(x = factor(smoke_gas_exposure), y = bmi, fill = factor(smoke_gas_exposure))) +

  labs(x = "Smoke/Gas Exposure", y = "BMI", fill = "Smoke/Gas Exposure") +
  ggtitle("BMI by Smoke/Gas Exposure")

    The gas stove exposure has the highest BMI of all the categories by far and the second hand smoke is the smallest by a good margin as well. It is interesting to see how much of a spike there is for the gas stove exposure and BMI when the FEV one earlier showed a high amount for second hand smoke exposure vs.Â in this bar graph, there is a lesser amount and the third highest bar.

  5. A leaflet map showing the concentrations of PM2.5 mass in each of the CHS communities.

    library(leaflet)

  )

    There appears to be a lot more dots in the East LA region compared to the San Luis Obispo area close to San Diego, this is interesting because you would think the data would show some more communities inside of LA due to the diversity of the city but the closest is 1 in Burbank and 1 in Long Beach.

  6. Choose a visualization to examine whether PM2.5 mass is associated with FEV.

    ggplot(imputemerge, aes(x = pm25_mass, y = fev, color = pm25_mass)) +

The lower pm2.5 mass proportion of this study appear to have the highest sample size and the highest and lowest values. The third quadrant we see also has a lot of samples and like all 4 of the main scatters presented, majority of the FEV results fall in the 1500-2500 fev range.
